8 tsibble and tidyverse pipelines
Because tsibble extends tibble, pipelines feel natural:
data |&gt;
  as_tsibble(index = date, key = id) |&gt;
  filter(date &gt;= yearmonth("2019 Jan")) |&gt;
  group_by(id) |&gt;
  summarise(mean_value = mean(value, na.rm = TRUE))
The difference is not syntax — it is semantics.

4 Pipes are not magic
The pipe does not change what functions do.
It only changes how inputs are passed.


4.1 Without pipes
summarise(
  group_by(
    mutate(
      filter(df, value &gt; 0),
      log_value = log(value)
    ),
    id
  ),
  mean_value = mean(log_value)
)


4.2 With pipes
df |&gt;
  filter(value &gt; 0) |&gt;
  mutate(log_value = log(value)) |&gt;
  group_by(id) |&gt;
  summarise(mean_value = mean(log_value))








Tip



If you can rewrite a pipeline as nested function calls,
then the pipeline is doing exactly what you think it is.

